<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="applications">
  <title>Part 4: Applications of Logic</title>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Translate the following English statements into logical expressions:

      <ol type="a">
        <li>
          If the alarm is set and the window is open, then the siren sounds.
          Let <m>a</m>: The alarm is set, <m>w</m>: The window is open, <m>s</m>: The siren sounds
        </li>

        <li>
          If the power is out, then the lights are off or the generator is on.
          Let <m>p</m>: Power is out, <m>l</m>: Lights are off, <m>g</m>: Generator is on
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Determine if the following argument is valid. Justify your answer.

      <blockquote>
        If I study, then I will pass the exam.<br/>
        I did not pass the exam.<br/>
        Therefore, I did not study.
      </blockquote>

      Let <m>s</m>: I study, <m>p</m>: I pass the exam.  
      Form: <m>s \rightarrow p</m>, <m>\neg p</m>, therefore <m>\neg s</m>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Use truth tables to determine if the following are logically equivalent:

      <ol type="a">
        <li><m>p \rightarrow q</m> and <m>\neg p \lor q</m></li>
        <li><m>\neg(p \land q)</m> and <m>\neg p \lor \neg q</m></li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      Prove or disprove:
      <me>
        p \rightarrow (q \land r) \equiv (p \rightarrow q) \land (p \rightarrow r)
      </me>
      using a truth table.
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</section>